Memory Triage with Volatility/rekall
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Volatility framework for memory analysis
Capture memory dumps from a running Linux system
Analyze memory dumps to identify running processes and system artifacts
Extract volatile data that could be lost during system shutdown
Understand the importance of memory forensics in incident response
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of operating system processes and memory management
Familiarity with file system navigation
Root/sudo access on the Linux machine
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated Linux environment. The provided machine is bare metal with no pre-installed forensic tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab exercises.

Task 1: Environment Setup and Tool Installation
Subtask 1.1: Update System and Install Dependencies
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y python3 python3-pip git build-essential python3-dev libssl-dev
Subtask 1.2: Install Volatility Framework
# Install Volatility 3 (latest version)
pip3 install volatility3

# Verify installation
vol -h
Subtask 1.3: Install Memory Capture Tools
# Install LiME (Linux Memory Extractor)
sudo apt install -y linux-headers-$(uname -r)
git clone https://github.com/504ensicsLabs/LiME.git
cd LiME/src
make
cd ~/
Task 2: Memory Dump Capture
Subtask 2.1: Create Memory Dump Directory
mkdir ~/memory_analysis
cd ~/memory_analysis
Subtask 2.2: Capture Memory Dump Using LiME
# Load LiME kernel module and capture memory
sudo insmod ~/LiME/src/lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=./memory_dump.lime format=lime"

# Verify dump creation
ls -lh memory_dump.lime
Subtask 2.3: Alternative Memory Capture Method
# If LiME fails, use dd method (less reliable but functional)
sudo dd if=/dev/mem of=./memory_dump_dd.raw bs=1M count=1024 2>/dev/null
Task 3: Memory Analysis with Volatility
Subtask 3.1: Identify Memory Profile
# For Linux memory dumps, identify the system profile
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.banner
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.info
Subtask 3.2: Process Analysis
# List running processes
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.pslist

# Show process tree
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.pstree

# Find hidden processes
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.psaux
Subtask 3.3: Network Connections Analysis
# Display network connections
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.netstat

# Show listening sockets
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.lsof
Subtask 3.4: File System Analysis
# List mounted filesystems
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.mount

# Show open files
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.lsof | head -20
Subtask 3.5: Extract Process Memory
# Dump specific process memory (replace PID with actual process ID)
vol -f memory_dump.lime -o ./extracted/ linux.proc.Maps --pid 1234

# Extract bash history from memory
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.bash
Task 4: Advanced Memory Artifacts
Subtask 4.1: Kernel Module Analysis
# List loaded kernel modules
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.lsmod

# Check for suspicious modules
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.check_modules
Subtask 4.2: System Call Analysis
# Examine system call table
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.check_syscall

# Look for process command lines
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.psaux | grep -E "(bash|sh|python|perl)"
Subtask 4.3: Memory Strings Analysis
# Extract strings from memory dump
strings memory_dump.lime | grep -E "(password|user|admin|root)" | head -10

# Look for IP addresses in memory
strings memory_dump.lime | grep -E "([0-9]{1,3}\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}" | head -10
Task 5: Documentation and Reporting
Subtask 5.1: Create Analysis Report
# Generate comprehensive report
echo "Memory Forensics Analysis Report" > analysis_report.txt
echo "=================================" >> analysis_report.txt
echo "Date: $(date)" >> analysis_report.txt
echo "" >> analysis_report.txt

# Add process information
echo "Running Processes:" >> analysis_report.txt
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.pslist >> analysis_report.txt

# Add network connections
echo -e "\nNetwork Connections:" >> analysis_report.txt
vol -f memory_dump.lime linux.netstat >> analysis_report.txt
Subtask 5.2: Verify Analysis Results
# Check report size and content
wc -l analysis_report.txt
head -20 analysis_report.txt
Verification Steps
Confirm memory dump creation: ls -lh memory_dump.lime
Verify Volatility installation: vol --help
Check analysis output: cat analysis_report.txt | wc -l
Validate extracted data: Review process lists and network connections
Common Issues and Solutions
LiME compilation errors: Ensure kernel headers match running kernel version
Permission denied: Use sudo for memory access operations
Large memory dumps: Use head or tail commands to view partial outputs
Missing profiles: Volatility 3 auto-detects Linux profiles
Cleanup
# Remove kernel module
sudo rmmod lime

# Clean up large files if needed
rm -f memory_dump.lime memory_dump_dd.raw
Conclusion
You have successfully completed memory forensics analysis using Volatility framework. This lab demonstrated how to capture volatile system memory and extract critical forensic artifacts including running processes, network connections, and system information. Memory analysis is crucial in incident response as it captures data that would be lost when a system is powered down, providing investigators with real-time system state information that can reveal malicious activities, hidden processes, and network communications.

These skills are essential for cybersecurity professionals, digital forensics investigators, and incident response teams who need to analyze compromised systems and understand attacker behavior through memory artifacts.
